Given the following code
```rust
#![warn(warnings, unused)]

fn main() {
    let x = 13;
}
```
running `rustc -A unused test.rs` shows a warning that `x` is unused as expected (since the module scope takes precedence over the command-line arguments). However, `rustc -A warnings` prints nothing.

This is caused by the following special handling:

https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/blob/01ffbcbeed39b71c9939c7e67e39e59a5a09b254/src/librustc_session/session.rs#L1178-L1189

The FIXME already describes the problem, but I haven't found an open issue for this.

The special case was introduced by [this commit](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/commit/abc56a011a0c00ac85a896957ff6182d3d86f4aa) as part of https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/21248. Looks like it is a hack needed to silence some otherwise unsilenceable warnings -- but I am not sure if the hack is still needed, or if there isn't a better way to do this.
